@attribute [Route(PageRoute.ReconnectModal)]
@attribute [HUIPageSettings("Reconnect modal")]
@using Brism

<DemoPageLayout TItem="ReconnectModal" HUIComponent="typeof(HUIReconnectModal)">
    <HUIReconnectModal />

    <MudText>
        <strong>1. Place the component</strong>
        <CodeBlock Language="CodeLanguage.Razor" Code="@(@"<HUIReconnectModal />")"></CodeBlock>
        in the body of your App.razor page. It should be right above your blazor js import.
    </MudText>

    <MudText>
        <strong>2. Set autostart to false</strong>
        <CodeBlock Language="CodeLanguage.Razor" Code="@(@"<script src=""_framework/blazor.web.js"" autostart=""false""></script>")"></CodeBlock>
    </MudText>


    <MudText>
        <strong>3. Import boot js</strong>
        <CodeBlock Language="CodeLanguage.Razor" Code="@(@"<script src=""@Assets[""_content/Hedin.UI/js/boot-server.js""]""></script>")"></CodeBlock>
    </MudText>

    <MudText>If you are running blazor webasm then you need to implement your own boot.js script. Microsoft has an example <MudLink Underline="Underline.Always" Href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/aspnet/core/blazor/fundamentals/signalr?view=aspnetcore-9.0#automatically-refresh-the-page-when-server-side-reconnection-fails">here</MudLink></MudText>
    <MudText>The same way you could of course implement your own blazor server reconnect logic too. Replace boot-server.js by your own javascript.</MudText>
</DemoPageLayout>



